<h1>Audit trail</h1>
<p>The audit trail keeps a record of all important activities and changes made in your application.</p>
<h4>Further help</h4>
<p><a href="#" data-page="56">Audit configuration</a><br>
<a href="#" data-page="57">Add audit admin note</a><br>
<a href="#" data-page="58">View audit trail</a></p>
</div>

<div id="p56" style="display:none">
<h1>Auditing configuration</h1>
<p>By default, the audit trail only records changes. However, for some applications, it is useful to record when users read information.</p>
<p>You can configure the application to audit:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Item display: Whenever an item is displayed to a user.</li>
	<li>Searches: Any search made by a user. Note that a search will display titles and summaries of the found items.</li>
	<li>File downloads: Whenever a file is downloaded by a user.</li>
</ul>
<p>These apply whether the user reading is information in the main web interface, API access, or mobile app.</p>
<p>Exports of information, and changing these settings are always audited.</p>
<h2>Plugins and auditing</h2>
<p>Plugins can implement their own rules for auditing these optional entries, and the configuration you set is only a default.</p>
<p>Plugins should declare their rules for auditing, and these will be displayed on the configuration page. However, accuracy cannot be guaranteed, so you should check with the authors of plugins if you have any doubts.</p>
</div>

<div id="p57" style="display:none">
<h1>Add audit admin note</h1>
<p>Sometimes it is useful to annotate the audit trail, for example, to explain recent activity or the intent of configuration in the audit trail. Adding an admin note to the trail allows you to add a human readable note.</p>
<p>Because the audit trail is write-only, any note you enter is not editable and it is not possible to delete it.</p>
</div>

<div id="p58" style="display:none">
<h1>View audit trail</h1>
<p>The audit trail viewer allows you to see all audited activity within your application.</p>
<p>To find entries of particular interest, use the filters along the top of the listing.</p>
<ul>
	<li>Date: Enter a date in YYYY-MM-DD format to filter to all audit entries on or before that date.</li>
	<li>Type: The kind of audit entry to display.</li>
	<li>User: Show only activities of a given user. You only need to enter a partial name.</li>
	<li>Item: Show only entries about a particular item in the system. Use the reference from the item&#8217;s URL.</li>
	<li>Entity: If you have filtered by a kind, you can narrow it down to a particular entity.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div id="p59" style="display:none">
<h1>Term inclusion specifications</h1>
<p>When an object links to another object, the search behaves as if some of the text from the linked object appears in the linking object. So if an object linked to another object with a title &#8216;Example&#8217;, everything will work as if the text &#8216;Example&#8217; was included in an attribute.</p>
<p>The end result is that the search will work as a user expects. They see &#8216;Example&#8217; in an attribute of an object, and searching for &#8216;Example&#8217; will find that object.</p>
<p>A &#8220;term inclusion specification&#8221; allows you to control exactly what terms (text) is included in the linking object.</p>
<p>Text from the <em>title</em> attribute is always included, and this cannot be overridden since it would yield unexpected results. But you can use the specification to include other fields and change the relative weightings.</p>
<p>Each line of the specification looks like</p>
<pre>   weighting attribute-name</pre>
<p>Where <em>weighting</em> is a number, and <em>attribute-name</em> is the search name of an attribute.</p>
<p>If an attribute is mentioned, any terms from the text in that attribute is included. For example,</p>
<pre>   2.0 title
   0.25 notes</pre>
<p>includes text from the title, boosted in relevance, and from the notes, with reduced relevance.</p>
<p>Term inclusion can only include terms from text values. It won&#8217;t include anything from, for example, links to other objects.</p>
<p>Use term inclusion with caution, as it may cause your search results to include unexpected items.</p>
</div>

